-- Ex Falso Quodlibet (From False, Anything Follows)
--
-- STATUS: EXECUTABLE (Issue #107 - incorrectly claimed no content)
-- This file HAS executable content: the `derive anything` statement (line 27)
-- uses ex_falso to derive Anything @ 1 from absurdity @ 0. The checker
-- parses and validates this. The surrounding comments explain the semantics.
--
-- Classical: False -> A (for any A)
-- CredTT: When c = 0, any conditional is admissible (limit)
--
-- Example: From contradiction, derive arbitrary statement
-- Classical: Instant explosion, any A follows
-- CredTT: GRADED explosion, constraint vanishes at c=0

-- Classical ex falso is INSTANTANEOUS:
-- One false premise -> immediate explosion to anything

-- CredTT ex falso is CONTINUOUS:
-- As credence -> 0, constraints gradually vanish

-- c = 1: Fully constrained, normal derivation rules apply
-- c = 0.5: Weakly constrained, some derivations become admissible
-- c = 0.1: Very weakly constrained, most things admissible
-- c = 0: Unconstrained, ANYTHING admissible (ex falso)

-- This is the spectrum classical logic hides!

-- A proposition at zero credence
postulate absurdity : False @ 0

-- EXECUTABLE: derive anything from zero credence
derive anything : Anything @ 1 from absurdity by ex_falso

-- This works because ex_falso checks that absurdity has credence 0,
-- then allows deriving ANY proposition at credence 1 (vacuously true)

-- From zero credence, anything follows at credence 1
-- This is because P(A|False) is undefined/vacuous
-- We can set it to any value, including 1

-- Classical: False |- A
-- CredTT: False @ 0 |- A @ 1 (vacuous truth)

-- The math: P(A,B) = P(A|B) * P(B)
-- When P(B) = 0: P(A,B) = P(A|B) * 0 = 0
-- ANY value of P(A|B) satisfies this!
-- So P(A|B) is unconstrained when P(B) = 0

-- Why this matters:
-- In classical logic, ex falso is mysterious
-- "From false, anything follows" - but WHY?
--
-- In CredTT, it's clear:
-- Zero credence means zero constraint
-- The chain rule P(A,B) = P(A|B)*P(B) is trivially satisfied
-- when P(B) = 0, no matter what P(A|B) is

-- The graded spectrum:
-- c = 0.01: Very weak constraint, P(A|B) almost free
-- c = 0.001: Weaker still
-- c = 0: No constraint at all

-- CredTT makes this VISIBLE; classical logic makes it INVISIBLE
